{"id":"2109.02718","submitter":"B\\'oris Marin","authors":"Gustavo Menesse, B\\'oris Marin, Mauricio Girardi-Schappo, Osame\n  Kinouchi","title":"Homeostatic Criticality in Neuronal Networks","comments":"17 pages, 7 figures","journal-ref":"Chaos Solitons Fractals 156 (2022) 111877","doi":"10.1016/j.chaos.2022.111877","report-no":null,"categories":"nlin.AO cond-mat.dis-nn cond-mat.stat-mech q-bio.NC","license":"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/4.0/","abstract":"  In self-organized criticality (SOC) models, as well as in standard phase\ntransitions, criticality is only present for vanishing external fields $h \\to\n0$. Considering that this is rarely the case for natural systems, such a\nrestriction poses a challenge to the explanatory power of these models. Besides\nthat, in models of dissipative systems like earthquakes, forest fires, and\nneuronal networks, there is no true critical behavior, as expressed in clean\npower laws obeying finite-size scaling, but a scenario called \"dirty\"\ncriticality or self-organized quasi-criticality (SOqC). Here, we propose simple\nhomeostatic mechanisms which promote self-organization of coupling strengths,\ngains, and firing thresholds in neuronal networks. We show that with an\nadequate separation of the timescales for the coupling strength and firing\nthreshold dynamics, near criticality (SOqC) can be reached and sustained even\nin the presence of significant external input. The firing thresholds adapt to\nand cancel the inputs ($h$ decreases towards zero). Similar mechanisms can be\nproposed for the couplings and local thresholds in spin systems and cellular\nautomata, which could lead to applications in earthquake, forest fire, stellar\nflare, voting, and epidemic modeling.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 6 Sep 2021 20:06:54 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Mon, 20 Sep 2021 18:34:00 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Thu, 3 Feb 2022 17:57:28 GMT"}],"update_date":"2022-02-14"}
